 aDespite Soho’s rich cultural history, there remains an absence of work on the depiction of the popular neighbourhood in film. Soho on Screen provides one of the first studies of Soho within postwar British cinema. Drawing upon historical, cultural and urban studies of the area, this book explores twelve films and theatrically released documentaries from a filmography of over one hundred Soho set productions. While predominantly focusing on low-budget, exploitation films which are exemplars of British and international filmmaking, Young also offers new readings of star and director biographies, from Laurence Harvey to Emeric Pressburger, and in so doing enlivens discussion on filmmaking in a time and place of intense social transformation, technological innovation and growing permissiveness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aMotion pictureszEnglandxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aFilm and Television Studies, Media Studies.1 aBradshaw, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831109976680 cprintz978180073477740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978180073478440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800734784423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800734784/original  a978-3-11-099766-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles